    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why do they use that word? is there something actually weird or unsettling about the way it works compared to normal physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was initially skeptical of entanglement. He felt that it was \"spooky\" because it seemed to defy classical notions of space and time. The phrase captures the idea that entanglement allows for instantaneous communication between particles, which is not allowed by classical physics. It's not that the phenomenon is inherently weird or unsettling, but rather that it challenges our intuitive understanding of the physical world. Einstein's discomfort with entanglement was rooted in his strong adherence to the principles of locality and causality, which are fundamental to classical physics.",
      "source": "target",
